<F P=101> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia, Kazakhstan To Launch Satellites With SS-18 Missiles </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0103183794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1643 GMT 1 Mar 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD0103183794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russia and Kazakhstan intend to use 
inter-continental military missiles SS-18 for launching 
commercial satellites to the round the Earth orbit (up to 
1,000km). 
  Interfax has learnt about the project providing for the test 
launching of the missile with a simplified version of a 
satellite. The project is to demonstrate real possibility of the 
missile for launching commercial loads with the minimal changes 
in the docking unit. 
  Experts believe the missile may put into orbit the load 
weighing about 600 kilos and it could be used for implementing 
the existing programmes of satellite communication systems on 
the basis of low-orbit satellites. 
  A representative of the Russian Space Agency who has a 
direct 
involvement to the implementation of the project with the use of 
SS-18, has told Interfax that so far the launching of the 
missile is in question because the Russian Military Space force, 
which control missile systems and space vehicles, has not OKed 
the project. 
  The spokesman did not rule out the possibility that the 
problem would be raised at the talks on conditions of leasing 
the space center Baykonur and the military cooperation in Almaty 
that are to begin in a week (the Russian delegation will leave 
for Almaty on March 9) 
  Missiles SS-18 are to be destroyed in line with the 
Russian-U.S. treaty START-2 before the year 2003. Now 104 SS-18 
missiles are based in Kazakhstan. 

</TEXT>

