<H3> <TI>   Overview of Armament Exports in 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0102151894 Bern ATSA/SDAA in French 1104 GMT 31 Jan 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0102151894 </F>
<F P=104>  Bern ATSA/SDAA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Slight Increase in Armament Exports </F>
from Switzerland -- Malaysia Was the Biggest Customer in 1993"; 
as released by Bern ATSA/SDAA database] 
  [Text] Bern, 31 Jan (ATS) -- In 1993, arms exports 
increased by 0.5 percent in comparison with the year before, 
from 258.8 million [Swiss] francs (Sf) to Sf260.2 million. 
However, taking inflation into account, the figure represents a 
decrease in real terms, Francois Godet, deputy secretary general 
of the Federal Military Department (DMF), told ATS. 
  Since 1987's record figure (Sf578.3 million), the amount of 
arms exports has fallen each year. Mr. Godet says that this 
downward trend can be explained by the increased arms sales by 
"threshold countries," such as the former Communist countries in 
Eastern Europe. 
<H5>  European Union as the Main Customer </H5>
  In 1993, Switzerland's biggest individual customer was 
Malaysia, with sales amounting to Sf50.7 million. Germany 
ranked second (Sf41.5 million), followed by Saudi Arabia (Sf36.9 
million). From a geographical point of view, the European Union 
is the main purchaser of Swiss arms at Sf79.1 million, followed 
by the United Arab Emirates and Saudi Arabia, both totaling Sf45 
million. 
  Other major customers include Sweden and Singapore (Sf16 
million each), Canada (11.9 million), the United States (Sf8.6 
million), Austria (Sf7.6 million), the Philippines (Sf4.1 
million), the Netherlands (Sf3.8 million), and Brazil (Sf1.4 
million). The smallest customer was Estonia, which spent Sf21 
[as received] for explosives and chemicals for civil use. 

</TEXT>

