<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Attending Swiss Trade Fair on N-Waste, Other Services </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0403154794 Bern ATSA/SDAA in French 1050 GMT 4 Mar 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0403154794 </F>
<F P=104>  Bern ATSA/SDAA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed ME/PI: "Bale: Three Federal Councillors </F>
Present at Opening of Muba 94"; as released by Bern ATSA/SDAA 
database] 
  [Excerpt] Bale, 4 Mar (ATS) -- The Muba, the most important 
public trade fair in Switzerland, opened on Friday. Three 
federal councillors attended the opening. For 10 days more than 
1,400 exhibitors will display their services and products in 
seven distinct sectors. The special presentations this year are 
dedicated to AIDS, civil protection, radioactive waste, and 
rational energy use. 
  Federal Councillors Jean-Pascal Delamuraz, Arnold Koller, 
and 
Swiss President Otto Stich attended the first day of Muba 1994. 
Among the people invited were Lonnart Meri, president of the 
Republic of Estonia; Mario Frick, head of the Liechtenstein 
Government; Gret Haller, president of the Swiss National 
Council; and Riccardo Jagmetti, president of the Swiss State 
Council. 
  [Public Economic Councillor] Jean-Pascal Delamuraz delivered 
a speech in which he said: "There is hope of a modest recovery, 
but we should also be aware that the economic recovery will not 
have an immediate affect on the labor market." He reminded his 
audience that the parliament will have to decide this autumn on 
whether to accept the new GATT agreements. These agreements, he 
said, are "good and even indispensable for Switzerland, but they 
will not perform miracles." They are aimed at entrepreneurs and 
"bold" workers, and are not "for the faint-hearted." 
<H5>  Fifteen Trading Partners </H5>
  This year, Muba is acting as host to 15 trading partners. 
Estonia, Kenya, the DPRK, and the region of Offenburg/Mid-Baden 
(Germany) are represented for the first time. The other guest 
countries are India, Mongolia, Pakistan, Poland, Russia, the 
Slovak Republic, Sri Lanka, Thailand, the Czech republic, 
Hungary, and the French region of Vosges. [passage omitted) 

</TEXT>

