<H3> <TI>   Iranians' Extradition Case Referred to French Council of State </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1702130994 Bern ATSA/SDAA in French 2019 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> BR1702130994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bern ATSA/SDAA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed SK/UC/LL: "Non-Extradition Of Two Iranians </F>
By France: Federal Council Refers Matter To French Council Of 
State"; as released by Bern ATSA/SDAA database] 
  [Excerpts] Bern, 16 Feb (ATS) -- The Federal Council 
decided Wednesday to refer to the French Council of State 
following France's refusal to extradite two Iranians. [see pp. 
5-6 of 12 January 1994 Terrorism Report for report of Iranians' 
expulsion] France's highest administrative court will have to 
determine whether France violated the European Convention on 
Extradition. In the eyes of the Swiss government, the 
credibility of the fight against terrorism is at stake, Federal 
Council Member Arnold Koller said. The Council of State 
confirmed Wednesday that this appeal is admissible. [background 
passage omitted] 
<H5>  Respect Its Commitments </H5>
  The Federal Council feels that France has violated the 
European Convention on Extradition of 1957. This instrument is 
based on reciprocity and the obligation to provide a reason for 
any refusal of a request for extradition. Its legal force 
depends on the relations of confidence between the contracting 
countries regarding respect of human rights. The Swiss aim is 
to obtain a court ruling of one state's failure to comply with 
international commitments. 
  A single breach in the system endangers the credibility of 
the fight against terrorism, Arnold Koller stressed. It is for 
this reason of principle that the Federal Council decided to 
bring the matter before a legal authority. 
<H5>  Big Surprise </H5>
  Arnold Koller reiterated that Switzerland was all the more 
surprised by its neighbor's attitude since the French 
authorities announced four times that the extradition would take 
place. The surprise was also reinforced by the fact that in 
1991 and 1992 Switzerland extradited to France two Iranians 
wanted for participating in the assassination of the former 
Iranian Prime Minister Shapur Bakhtiar. 
  The French Council of State has a twofold mission: that of 
the supreme administrative court guaranteeing fundamental rights 
and liberties, and that of adviser to the government in drafting 
laws. Since 1977, it has also been referred to in contested 
extradition cases. [passage omitted on French comments] 
<H5>  The Inquiry Continues </H5>
  Switzerland's action vis-a-vis the Council of State 
"overjoyed" Roland Chatelain, the examining magistrate for the 
canton of Vaud. He has not closed the file and is continuing his 
investigation into the responsibility of the Iranians -- 13 in 
all -- who are suspected in the assassination of Kazem Radjavi. 
Ernst Muehlemann, chairman of the Foreign Policy Committee of 
the Swiss National Council, also welcomed the Federal Council's 
decision. 

</TEXT>

